anyone know where the BMW M3 GTR‚Äôs are in the world & how many were made?

In order to homologate the M3 GTR for racing  a road version was developed during calendar year 2001 and shown for the first time at the season ending ALMS Petit Le Mans race. BMW produced 10 development units of which 3 were production ready display cars. For homologation purposes  the M3 GTR needed to be offered for sale to the general public and by Petit Le Mans 2001  the car was ready. The M3 GTR was to be priced at‚Ç¨250 000 [86]When ALMS changed the homologation rules at the end of the 2001 season  the road version project was stopped. All 7 development prototypes were recycled but the three production ready display cars exist to this day and all still owned by BMW AG. One of the Road M3 GTRs was displayed by BMW of North America LLC atLegends of the Autobahnin 2015 along with the newly restored ALMS race version of the car.[87]The road cars were built alongside bodies-in-white of the GTR race cars in the special vehicles department of BMW's Regensburg Plant.
Basically they followed the rulebook that said that they needed to sell 10 road legal M3 GTR to homologate the M3 GTR race car

When the rules were changed to become 100 (because Porsche complained TEACHER  BMW IS CHEATING) BMW decided to scrap the road car program (7 recycled  the remaining 3 are still with BMW) and discontinue the M3 GTR racing program

Production of the Essenza SCV12 is limited to 40 units. The car is not legal for road use and is planned to have its own one-make racing series. The cars will be stored in a special hangar built near the Sant'Agata factory with the owners having the ability to monitor their cars via an app linked to security cameras. Lamborghini would let the customer take delivery of their car upon request  akin to Maserati who allowed customers to take delivery of theMC12 Versione Corse. Lamborghini is responsible for the maintenance and transportation of the cars to any one of the FIA class 1 tracks around the world  in the case that the owner does not wish to keep the car. Customers can also receive coaching from Lamborghini racing driversEmanuele PirroandMarco Mapelli.

What do yall think of the lexus LFA
WAT?! WAT?! WAT DID U SAY?!I CANT HEAR YOU OVER THE SOUND OF MY GLORIOUS 4.8 LITRE V10 AT 9000RPM DESIGNED BY PIANO COMPANY
It's one of what I consider the last of the old school sports cars
RWD  high rev NA big cc engine. Very analog car
No turbos  no hybrid motors or batteries
don't take it the wrong way  but calling an LFA a sports car lowkey does the LFA a disservice itself üòÇ
Somewhat flawed  but where it excels  it has no equal
it sold like ass when it came out
sure  extremely well engineered  co-developed with Yamaha and brutally tested on the Nords.
but it has come to a point where every 12 year old jerks off to the thought of it
with a kerb weight of 1.6 tons and a dodgy 6 speed automated manual...?
Actually they made 500 of them only and that is what they sold
don't get me wrong  it is a marvel of a car
but they aren't all THAT great
It was never meant to be a big volume sports cars like the R35 GTR
it never was  but even then it never sold well.
It's a halo car  it actually lost money for Lexus for every unit
It was meant to be a marketing and branding exercise
if anything  the loss of the then-planned Honda NSX was a contribution to the lack of sales
"We can do this wonderful thing"
the NSX which turned into the HSV-010
the financial crisis played a part too.
It was not the fastest car when it came out  the R35 was faster
as much as one would kill for an LFA now  not many would've want to fork out the amount brand new
it was never about speed really
It was always about getting there fast  looking and sounding good
the LFA was meant as a huge "fuck you  we're incorporating every thing we've learnt from motorsports"
all while being comfortable and reliable enough to be a toyota
